^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's talk about the auction. Many people would bid 1S with my hand. But, the correct way to bid the hand with 5 card minor and 4 card major and game forcing values is to bid the minor first. Now, as to what North should bid over 2C. I play that 2S is still a reverse, showing extra values. However, many people who play 2 over 1 do not play that as a reverse. Each partnership has to decide. |
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The advantage of playing it as a reverse is that you can get to slam with 16 opposite 16 more easily, which normally is hard to do. The disadvantage is you sometimes have a rebid problem, as Patti did. On occasion she will have to rebid 2H with a 5 card suit, or bid 2N with a singleton as she did.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at| Therefore, you just have to make the tradeoff. Should you just be able to bid your shape without worrying about a reverse issue, or should you be able to show a stronger hand?  I favor the reverse showing a stronger hand theory, but bidding your shape has its merits as well.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Next, let's talk about the double. Dee does not have a bad double on the surface, although we did freely bid our game. However, by doubling she pinpointed how to play the hand. Please note 2N does not deny spades if you play 2S shows a reverse. That is one thing you have to consider when doubling the opponents. You may cost yourself a trick or two by pinpointing the play. |
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I was also lucky the Queen of clubs dropped. I figured I was probably down one. Further, I hope you noticed how I handled the spade spots. I made sure I could overtake the spade in my hand for the last finesse. That is part of planning the hand. |
