UP|37|NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I had a question as to what I recommend for preempting in first seat. Those of you who have been following my lessons for a long time already know the answer. I think you should preempt with any excuse, particularly at favorable vulnerability. That means if you have a 7 card suit, of any quality, and not an opening hand, you should preempt. But some people feel you need at least 2 honors. It is really a risk reward decisions. I think the rewards for preempting far outweigh the risks. Even if it turns out the bid theoretically won't work out, often times the opponents save you anyway.|
PG| ***** 36 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Some people have different guidelines for different seats. One interesting guideline that has merit is that your preempts in second seat should be sound. The reason for that is because your right hand opponent has passed and hence does not have a good hand. Therefore, the likelihood that your partner has a good hand is increased. For that reason, you are more likely to be preempting your partner in second seat. Further, the argument is that if partner can count on you for a solid preempt in second seat, he can better judge what to do. I love to preempt so much that I don't follow that rule. But it has merit for sure.|
PG| ***** 37 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One comment on Dee's opening lead. I had a recent discussion with Marty Bergen about leading singletons and he said something very interesting. He said that if led a singleton against a suit contract every time he had one, he felt he would have come out ahead even if it was the opponent's suit and even if it was an honor. He is not advocating you always lead a singleton, but is saying it often is a strong lead. Of course not a singleton trump, just another suit. I suspect he would have led the three of spades with Dee's hand, as opposed to the Jack of diamonds.|
PG| ***** 38 ***** |


