NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Further, since Roberta is probably short in spades, it is even more likely she has diamonds. So, Patti is right, to evaluate her hand as 21 Dummy Points in support of diamonds. Thus, 2S is a good bid, and once Roberta bids 3C, which should show extra values, they are off to the races. 3H was an Italian control bid, showing first or 2nd round control of hearts. Further, Patti is too strong to bid splinter and it takes up too much room. |
PG| ***** 114 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Next, I like to discuss responses to RKCB with a void. You can decide to ignore the void, but in this case, because the void is in my suit, it should not be ignored. So, if you have a void and want to show it in response to RKCB, you do the following:|
PG| ***** 115 ***** |


NT|^B@2
1. With an even number of controls (2 or 4, usually not 0), you bid 5N which shows even ## of controls plus an unspecified void.

2. With an odd number of controls (1 or 3), you bid six of your void if it is below the agreed upon suit. |
PG| ***** 116 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, had her void been in clubs, Roberta would bid 6C. If the void is above her suit, then you bid six of your suit. In this case, had Roberta bid 6D over 4N, that shows 1 or 3 controls plus a void in hearts or spades. And it would be pretty clear that the void was in spades given this auction. I am not sure Patti should bid 7, although it is not a bad contract, even without the Ace of spades lead. Getting to six was just fine.|
PG| ***** 117 ***** |


